column12: APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR TRACKING THE LOCATION AND POSITION OF AN INDIVIDUAL
column13: An apparatus and method and provided for tracking the location and direction of an individual utilizing a direct radio frequency link between a mobile target (10) and a mobile monitor (20). The apparatus and method utilize a mobile target device which may be affixed to an individual to be tracked utilizing a secure attachment mechanism. A mobile monitor device in bi-directional communication with the mobile target device is additionally provided. This radio frequency communication is encrypted in nature, thereby preventing unauthorized tracking of an individual by a non-intended third party. The mobile monitor device determines the relative distance and direction between the mobile monitor device and mobile target device to a mobile monitor operator. A Bluetooth enabled microprocessor may be utilized in transmitting and receiving this encrypted signal. Based upon data derived from the radio frequency information received by a mobile monitor, a relative distance and direction from a mobile monitor to a mobile target may be computed. Data may also be received from both an external position locating apparatus and an accelerometer and converted into both position and direction of travel information.
column15: DUNCAN CHARLES

column12: Adapter for air conditioning connector
column13: An electrical connectivity disc ( 100, 130, 200 ) includes a plurality of serrated slots ( 106, 108 ) positioned about the disc. The disc preferably includes a plurality of barbs ( 136 ) about a peripheral edge ( 104 ) of the disc ( 130 ). A center aperture ( 110 ) can be formed in a center of the disc ( 130 ). A portion of the serrated slots ( 108 ) can be located in communication with the center aperture ( 110 ). The discs ( 130 ) are inserted into a generally an electrically conductive, cylindrical tubular structure ( 160 ). A cable ( 190 ) is inserted into a receiving aperture ( 168 ) and crimped providing an electro-mechanical interface with the tubular structure ( 160 ). The cable ( 190 ) provides an electrical connection to an air conditioning power input terminal block.

column12: Message format and flow control for replacement of the packet control driver/packet interface dual port RAM communication
column13: The architecture of the present invention provides a new message set and/or flow control mechanism and a networked architecture for managing telecommunication devices such as telephones, fax, voicemail, e-mail, and other communication endpoints. The new message set and flow control mechanism maps to existing (conventional) dual port RAM queues, tables, interrupts, and other memory locations, thus removing hardware dependency on the packet control driver/packet interface communications and allowing control of LAPD links to be remoted.

column12: Dual motor systems and non-rotating sensors for use in developing wellbores in subsurface formations
column13: A method for forming a subsurface wellbore is disclosed. The method includes operating a drilling string in a first direction of rotation. A first motor located near the end of the drilling string is operated in a direction of rotation opposite that of the drilling string. A drill bit is rotated using a second motor that is coupled to the first motor.

column12: Mobile decontamination shelter
column13: The mobile decontamination shelter, for treating people contaminated by nuclear, biological or chemical materials, is formed from a number of modules that can be connected in a variety of different layouts, said modules including a washing module 1 and modules 2,3 for dressing and undressing. The washing module is preferably twice the size of the dressing/undressing modules and may be used independently with curtains or screens breaking up the internal space to form changing areas. Attachment points for connecting adjoining modules are preferably supplied on each side of each module and interchangeable panels may be located in each side wall to form doors, windows or blank walls as required. Effluent holding tanks designed to be fed by gravitational flow from the washing module may be formed in the base 18 of one or more of the modules or alternatively be located externally. Folding ramps may be provided to aid access to the modules and the ramps may act as doors when raised. The modules may be designed to facilitate alternative uses.
column15: GRAY DUNCAN CHARLES

column12: Stake puller with stake supporting back plate
column13: A stake puller (10) for use in removing a stake (4) lodged in the ground (2) utilizes a lever (12) and fulcrum (20) for mechanical advantage. The stake (4) is positioned between a blade means (30) fixed to the end of the lever and a back plate (40) pivotally attached to the blade means. When the user pivots the lever down, the stake is pinched between the forward edge (34) of the blade means (30) and the primary surface (42) of the back plate (40). The primary surface (42) is curved and diverges from the stake. This minimizes any bending or friction forces applied to the stake.

column12: Debris net/scaffolding frame lifting system
column13: A perimeter debris net lifting system employs a plurality of lifting units which support a debris net for a high rise-type construction structure. The lifting units comprise a pair of frame assemblies which are slidably coupled and essentially scale the structure to raise the debris net as construction progresses. Each of the frame assemblies are independently mountable to two floors of the structure. Each lifting unit is vertically displaced by disengaging one of the frame assemblies from its mounting engagement and lifting the frame assembly while the other frame assembly remains securely fixed to the structure. The debris net remains fully extended and functional during the vertical lifting process. The lifting units may also mount one or more scaffolding frames and a vertical debris net.
column15: DUNCAN CHARLES W

column12: Floor mounted mobile air circulator
column13: A floor mounted mobile air circulator comprising an air driving mechanism 2 (i.e. fan, turbine, compressor etc...) that draws air 3 in from an inlet orifice 4 at or near a floor and communicating the air from the air driving mechanism 2 through an upright/vertical air flow directing duct 6 and through an outlet orifice 5 at a sufficient velocity towards a ceiling to displace heated air trapped adjacent the ceiling so as to reduce a differential temperature gradient of the air between the floor and ceiling. Air may be drawn through lateral orifices (fig 2). The air circulator may be powered by mains electricity, an integral battery (fig 3) or separate battery (fig 4). Temperature sensors may record the air temperature at floor and ceiling levels and subsequently control the flow of air as a result of the recorded temperature gradient between the floor and ceiling (figs 5 & 6). The air circulator may comprise of a hose connection so that the air circulator may be connected to pressurised air supply (fig 8).

column12: Method and System for Discovering Ancestors using Genomic and Genealogic Data
column13: Described invention and its embodiments, in part, facilitate discovery of ‘Most Recent Common Ancestors’ in the family trees between a massive plurality of individuals who have been predicted to be related according to amount of deoxyribonucleic acids (DNA) shared as determined from a plurality of 3rd party genome sequencing and matching systems. This facilitation is enabled through a holistic set of distributed software Agents running, in part, a plurality of cooperating Machine Learning systems, such as smart evolutionary algorithms, custom classification algorithms, cluster analysis and geo-temporal proximity analysis, which in part, enable and rely on a system of Knowledge Management applied to manually input and data-mined evidences and hierarchical clusters, quality metrics, fuzzy logic constraints and Bayesian network inspired inference sharing spanning across and between all data available on personal family trees or system created virtual trees, and employing all available data regarding the genome-matching results of Users associated to those trees, and all available historical data influencing the subjects in the trees, which are represented in a form of Competitive Learning network. Derivative results of this system include, in part, automated clustering and association of phenotypes to genotypes, automated recreation of ancestor partial genomes from accumulated DNA from triangulations and the traits correlated to that DNA, and a system of cognitive computing based on distributed neural networks with mobile Agents mediating activation according to connection weights.

column12: Improved Automatic Scare Gun.
column13: 113,381. Duncan, F. C. May 15, 1917. Machine guns; cartridge hoppers and the like.-Consists of an automatic gun adapted to fire blank cartridges for scaring birds and animals, which will fire at intervals during the daylight, remain inoperative during the night, and recommence at daybreak. In the construction shown, the barrel a is fixed and the breech-block recoils against the action of a spring c to cock the firing-pin g. The firing-mechanism comprises a vertically sliding sear i, a sear-operating plunger having, at the bottom, a projection adapted to engage a projection i on the sear, and a bell-crank lever k, Fig. 2, connected at the top of the plunger and having its other end bearing on the periphery of a disk l which is rotated once in twenty-four hours. Part of the periphery of the disk is formed with teeth which oscillate the bell-crank lever k and fire the gun. A number of disks having differently spaced teeth may be provided. When the gun is fired, a projection g<3> on the firing-pin actuates a cranked lever n which disengages the plunger j from the sear. The cartridges are fed from a box magazine placed above the breech action and provided with two downwardly inclined retaining lips q.

column12: Dual motor systems and non-rotating sensors for use in developing wellbores in subsurface formations
column13: A method for forming a subsurface wellbore is disclosed. The method includes operating a drilling string in a first direction of rotation. A first motor located near the end of the drilling string is operated in a direction of rotation opposite that of the drilling string. A drill bit is rotated using a second motor that is coupled to the first motor.

column12: Process and apparatus for distillation
column13: <PICT:0802148/III/1> Residual monomers are stripped from crude polymers by mixing the crude polymer with steam in a vessel under reduced pressure, and conducting the mixture to the top of a distillation column, under reduced pressure, down which the polymer flows in countercurrent to more steam. Butadiene and styrene may be stripped from crude latex formed by their copolymerization in an aqueous medium. The latex, introduced by a pipe 5, is mixed with steam, introduced by a pipe 7, in a vessel 4 connected by a pipe 9 to a distillation column 11 under reduced pressure. The latex foam formed in vessel 4 is sucked into the column 11 through a T-piece 17 and the foam is broken by impact on the side of the column, the latex falling on to an imperforate top plate 14. During residence time of the latex above top plate 14, disengagement of steam and vaporization of styrene and butadiene occurs. This distillate passes through a pipe 22 and a condenser 23 to vessels 25 and 28, where the water layer is separated from the styrene. Butadiene vapour is removed through pipe 30, to which a pump is connected to evacuate the apparatus. Latex passes through a U-shaped downcomer 13, and then through a series of perforated plates 12, each provided with U-shaped downcomers, to a reservoir 18. More steam is introduced through a pipe 20 to remove monomers remaining in the latex. This steam causes further foaming and some of the latex is carried back up the column with the distillate, passing up a pipe 16 to meet incoming latex foam, whereupon all the foam is broken and the latex carried up pipe 16 is returned down the column. Two forms of the T-piece are described, together with a lay-out of a plant for stripping styrene and butadiene from crude polymer using a modified distillation column.

column12: Improvements relating to Wire Sewing or Stapling Machines.
column13: 15,321. Mackay, C. D. July 20. Stapling.-In a stapling or wire-sewing machine of the kind having a vertically-reciprocating head which carries the working parts and is actuated by a pedal and raised by a spring, the head and the reciprocating spindle are capable of rotary adjustment and of being removed laterally without dismounting any of the working parts ; a positive feed of the wire is derived from the stroke of the spindle, and is so arranged as to feed a uniform length of wire at each stroke of the pedal, whether or not a partial feed has previously been effected by an incomplete stroke. A head A, secured to a spindle C, is mounted in a bearing b on an arm B, and is actuated by a lever D operated by a pedal and spring. The head A contains mechanism for cutting, bending, and driving staples, and clinching them against an anvil E. The upper portion of the head A is cylindrical and slides in a flanged sleeve A<1>, which has a rotary adjustment in the bearing b and is clamped by a movable cap b<1> and screws b<2>, independent rotary movement of the sleeve and head being prevented by a tongue a<1> on the sleeve engaging a slot in a flange a<2> on the head. The lever D engages the spindle C by means of a collar d, Fig. 5, open at one side, so that by removing the cap b<1> the head A and spindle C may be removed laterally. The mechanism which draws wire F from a reel mounted on an arm f is carried by a bracket G bolted to the lower portion of the head A, and comprises two feed-rollers g<1> geared together by toothed wheels g<3>, g<4>. The roller g<1>, which is visible in Fig. 3, is mounted in a fork of a lever g<5> pivoted at g<6>, and is held in operative position by a spring g<7> engaging an adjusting-screw g<8>. The lever g<5> may be moved out of the operative positive by a cam lever g<9> bearing against the bracket G. The rollers g' are actuated by a ratchet-wheel g<10> on the spindle g<2>, engaged by a spring pawl g<12>, which is carried by a toothed sector g<11> operated by a toothed wheel g<13> and a rack c<1> bolted to the spindle C. To stop the feed when the required length of wire has been delivered, a fixed cam g<15> is so placed as to lift the pawl g<12> out of engagement with the ratchet-wheel g<10>. In the event of an incomplete depression of the pedal the ratchetwheel effects a partial feed, and on the release of the pawl returns to its normal position. At the next complete depression of the pedal the remaining portion of the movement is imparted to the ratchet-wheel.

column12: Mount cutter
column13: A portable cutter, which provides a system of cutting at an angle (typically 45 degrees) the openings in picture mounts easily, accurately and safely, comprises a baseplate 2 an angled slide 1 and cutting knife holder 5 with pointed knife (8, Fig. 2). The mount is placed between the base and the angled slide and the knife holder is positioned on the slide opposite a corner. The pointed knife 8 is then pushed through the mount and the knife holder is gripped or pulled along the slide to effect the cutting. The resulting cut is angled along its length and at each end. The cutting action causes a downward pressure which holds the mount whilst the knife point is protected by entering a groove 4. One stop prevents the knife rotating in use and another locates it in an out-of-use position. <IMAGE>

column12: Inflatable articles
column13: Inflatable articles consist of or comprise a layer of a vulcanized rubbery copolymer of a di-olefine, e.g. butadiene or methyl butadiene and methyl isopropenyl ketone. Vulcanization of the copolymer may be effected by compounding the copolymer with carbon black, zinc oxide, stearic acid, sulphur and mixtures, accelerators such as N-cyclohexyl-2-benzthiazole sulphonamide, antioxidants such as condensation products of acetone and aniline and fillers such as calcium carbonate, pine tar, or wood resin. Inflatable articles metnioned are pneumatic tyres, tubeless pneumatic tyres, inner tubes, tennis balls and balloons.

column12: Antenna-mounting structure
column13: An antenna-mounting structure is disclosed for mounting an antenna to a vertical wall or on a sloped, peaked, or horizontal roof. A primary strut, which is tubular, has a straight, upper portion, a straight, intermediate portion, and a straight, lower portion. The upper portion has an outer, cylindrical surface, circular in cross-section, and is bent at an upper juncture between the upper and intermediate portions and at a lower juncture between the intermediate and lower portions. The upper and intermediate portions generally define an obtuse angle and the intermediate and lower portions generally define an acute angle. A secondary strut has a proximal end and a distal end is clamped at the proximal end of the secondary strut to the outer, cylindrical surface of the upper portion of the primary strut, above the upper juncture, so that the secondary strut can be adjustably oriented to project in any direction from the upper portion of the primary strut, and so that the secondary strut can be pivotally adjusted to any angle within a range so that the distal end can be higher than, level with, or lower than the proximal end.

column12: Method and system for stopping unnecessary processing conditional instructions of processor
column13: 本发明提供了一种用以终止处理器中一多时钟条件指令的非必要处理的方法与系统，当条件指令经由管线式程序来做处理时，管线至少包含一译码阶段、一执行阶段以及在这两者之间的一个或多个中间处理阶段。本方法会视一个或多个条件是否成立，来确定条件指令是否为可执行的。如果条件指令于译码阶段和执行阶段中皆会被处理，且条件指令于执行阶段中不会被执行时，则条件指令于译码阶段时就会被终止，也有可能于中间处理阶段被终止。提早终止如此的条件指令有助于处理器节省处理资源以及降低能源消耗。

column12: DEBRIS NET/SCAFFOLDING FRAME LIFTING SYSTEM
column13: 31 A perimeter debris net lifting system employs a plurality of lifting units which support a debris net for a high rise-type construction structure. The lifting units comprise a pair of frame assemblies which are slidably coupled and essentially scale the structure to raise the debris net as construction progresses. Each of the frame assemblies are independently mountable to two floors of the structure. Each lifting unit is vertically displaced by disengaging one of the frame assemblies from its mounting engagement and lifting the frame assembly while the other frame assembly remains securely fixed to the structure. The debris net remains fully extended and functional during the vertical lifting process. The lifting units may also mount one or more scaffolding frames and a vertical debris net.

column13: The present invention provides a grinding machine of the type comprising a pair of heavy rollers which define a nip through which the material, such as powdered clay, to be ground is passed. column12: PERIMETER DEBRIS NET LIFTING SYSTEM
column13: A perimeter debris net lifting system employs a plurality of lifting units which support a debris net for a high rise-type construction structure. The lifting units comprise a pair of frame assemblies which are slidably coupled and essentially scale the structure to raise the debris net as construction progresses. Each of the frame assemblies are independently mountable to two floors of the structure. Each lifting unit is vertically displaced by disengaging one of the frame assemblies from its mounting engagement and lifting the frame assembly while the other frame assembly remains securely fixed to the structure. The debris net remains fully extended and functional during the vertical lifting process. 36

In a polymerization process, monomer is fed to the reaction vessel by feeding means comprising a control device which is responsive to the temperature of reflux of monomer so that when the reflux temperature falls the monomer is fed to the reaction vessel, the supply of monomer being reduced when the reflux temperature rises and no monomer being supplied when the reflux temperature is above a predetermined value, the polymerization process being of the kind wherein only a proportion of the monomer or monomers is initially charged into the reaction vessel and the remainder is added while the polymerization proceeds under reflux at a temperature at which the monomer, or at least one of the monomers boils or forms a boiling mixture with another of the reaction constituents. In the apparatus shown, addition of monomer 6 and initiator 7 and the temperature in steam-water jacket 4 are controlled by means responsive to temperature sensing devices 14 (between reflux condenser 5 and vessel 1), 16, and 17. When the reflux temperature falls, monomer is fed in; when the rate of supply of monomer diminishes to a certain level, initiator is fed in. A booster mechanism is provided to raise the proportion of steam entering jacket 4 to complete the polymerization when all the monomer and initiator have been added.

column12: Floor mounted mobile air circulator
column13: A floor mounted mobile air circulator comprises an air driving mechanism 3 (i.e. fan, turbine, compressor etc...) that draws air 1 in from an inlet orifice 2 at or near a floor. The air is communicated from the air driving mechanism through an upright / vertical air flow directing duct 8 and through an outlet orifice 10 at a sufficient velocity utilising the Coanda effect towards a ceiling to displace heated air trapped adjacent the ceiling so as to reduce a differential temperature gradient of the air between the floor and ceiling. A main volume of air is entrained / drawn through lateral orifices 6 and does not pass through the air driving mechanism. The air circulator may be powered by mains electricity, an integral battery (fig 3) or separate battery (fig 4). Temperature sensors may record the air temperature at floor and ceiling levels and subsequently control the flow of air as a result of the recorded temperature gradient between the floor and ceiling (figs 5 & 6). The air circulator may comprise of a hose connection so that the air circulator may be connected to a pressurised air supply (fig 2).

column12: Gas monitoring system and method for in-seam drilling
column13: GAS MONITORING SYSTEM FOR IN-SEAM DRILLING A method and system for continuous monitoring gas content for in-seam drilling. The method comprises receiving a total gas rate signal derived from a pressure signal associated with drilling fluid and a bit depth signal tracking a bit depth of a drill bit over time. The method determines a baseline gas rate signal and a cuttings gas rate signal from the total gas signal. The cuttings gas rate signal is further determined based on the bit depth signal. The method also determines at least one property of the formation based on the bit depth signal, baseline gas rate signal and the cuttings gas rate signal to control in-seam drilling. C)

column12: Selective and persistent application level encryption for video provided to a client
column13: A system, apparatus, and method are directed towards allowing ingestion of encrypted content into such as a VOD server, or PVR, or the like by selectively encrypting portions of a content stream based on various selection rules. In one embodiment, the selection rules include leaving selected portions of the content stream unencrypted, including packets that include a PES header; or video packets that include various trick play data such as picture start, GOP start, sequence start, sequence end data; PIDs associated with a PAT, PMT, or the like; while other portions of the content stream may be encrypted, including video and/or audio PIDs, or other video and/or audio portions. In still another embodiment, Entitlement Control Messages (ECMs) may be inserted that employ an encryption/decryption key rotation scheme, such as odd and/or even scrambling control bit structures, which may also be rotated based on a variety of conditions.

column12: Low Energy Process for purifying water and reducing crop water consumption
column13: The low-energy water reclamation process consists of evaporation from water sources, followed by capturing, condensing and reusing the water released into the atmosphere from both the evaporation process and by plant transpiration. 95% to 99% of water from plant transpiration is lost by venting to the atmosphere. We capture that water, and reuse it, to grow food or provide potable water. Reclaiming and reusing the evaporated water reduces both the amount of new water required for plant growth or potable water production, and also reduces the total energy requirement for the process. Over a large growing area, we expect to reclaim a significant amount of transpired water, which will reduce the need for new water to grow food and/or provide pure unpolluted potable water, at lower total cost.

column12: Improvements in the production of polymeric products
column13: Stable aqueous dispersions of a copolymer of vinyl acetate and sym-dichloroethylene, in which the majority of particles of copolymer have a diameter of between 0.2 and 2 microns, are prepared by agitating at polymerization temperature a dispersion of vinyl acetate and sym-dichlorothylene, preferably the trans isomer thereof, in an aqueous medium containing a peroxygen compound such as ammonium or alkali metal persulphates, perborates and percarbonates, hydrogen peroxide, cumene hydroperoxide, and tert-butyl hydroperoxide, and an emulsion stabilizer comprising a protective colloid such as gum tragacanth, gum acacia, gelatine, glue, methyl cellulose, polyvinyl alcohol, or a water soluble partially hydrolysed polyvinyl carboxylic acid ester, and a polyethylene oxide/alcohol condensation product. The aqueous medium may also contain buffering agents such as sodium bicarbonate, and emulsifying agents such as ammonium and alkali metal salts of long chain aliphatic carboxylic acids, or a water soluble sulphonated long chain aliphatic alcohol, or an acid, ester or salt of such a compound. Copolymerization may be carried out by initially adding all the monomeric materials to the aqueous medium or by adding them gradually as the reaction proceeds. The aqueous dispersion so produced may be used for the production of impregnating and coating compositions by incorporating therein plasticizers such as dibutyl phthalate and tricresyl phosphate, and fillers such as barytes, ochre, lithopone, iron oxides, chalk and titanium dioxide. The plasticizer is preferably incorporated in the copolymer dispersion either by passing a mixture of plasticizer and dispersion through a homogenizer or by previously dispersing the plasticizer in water containing a dispersing agent compatible with the copolymer dispersion and subsequently mixing the plasticizer and copolymer dispersions. The Provisional Specification describes also the copolymerization in aqueous media of vinyl carboxylic acid esters with chlorinated alkenes other than those specified above such as trichloroethylene, perchloroethylene, and 1, 2-dichloropropene.

column12: DTMF Activated remote telephone line switching and testing
column13: DTMF (dual-tone multi-frequency) activated apparatus for remote switching and testing of a four-wire telephone line system is disclosed. The telephone line provides four-wire service between a first location and a plurality of second remote locations. By using a standard twelve button or expanded sixteen button telephone DTMF key pad, the switching and testing apparatus provides the capability at the first location of controlling switching circuits at any one of the remote locations. Each remote switching and testing circuit is provided with a DTMF detector and digital logic responsive to the detector for recognizing an assigned address code and any one of the command codes corresponding to the looped mode, the terminated mode, the milliwatt source mode, and the in-data mode. A programmable three digit address, for example, allows use of up to one thousand switching and testing circuits on one line. When the digital logic of a switching and testing circuit recognizes its assigned address, the circuit is enabled to respond to a following command code which causes the circuit to assume the corresponding mode. In addition to the four codes for each of the four modes of the switching and testing circuit, there is a "master reset" code which allows all units, or all units within a group, to be returned to the in-data mode.

column12: Improvements in the production of polymers from unsaturated compounds
column13: Aqueous polymer dispersions are made by slowly introducing a polymerizable unsaturated compound, e.g. as a gas, into an agitated aqueous medium comprising a dispersing agent, e.g. an emulsifier, a stabilizer and a catalyst, which is maintained under such conditions of temperature and pressure, i.e. normal, reduced or superatmospheric, that the unsaturated compound is rapidly vaporized from the medium, and withdrawing the vapours of the compound from the system, e.g. by distillation. Unsaturated compounds mentioned are vinyl acetate, acrylonitrile, methyl acrylate, butadiene, isoprene, and vinyl chloride. The emulsifying agent may be sulphonated long chain aliphatic alcohols, ammonium and alkali metal salts of long chain aliphatic carboxylic acids, or ethers of polyalkylene glycols with long chain aliphatic alcohols, e.g. oleyl. Specified stabilizers are gelatine, methyl cellulose, polyvinyl alcohol, gum acacia and gum tragacanth. The catalyst may be a per-compound, e.g. ammonium persulpate, hydrogen peroxide or a hydroperoxide, in conjunction, if desired, with a reducing agent such as a thiosulphate, sulphite, hydrosulphite, hydroxylamine or a water-soluble ferrous salt.

column12: Remote telephone line switching and testing
column13: Apparatus for remote switching and testing of a four-wire telephone line system is disclosed. The telephone line provides four-wire service between a first location and one or more second remote locations. The switching and testing apparatus provides the capability at the first location of controlling switching circuits at the remote location and making tests of the telephone line system including customer installed equipment. The telephone line, which will include a dedicated transmission path through at least one telephone company central office, is terminated at the respective customer premises by a terminating unit which provides a connection of customer installed equipment to the four-wire line. The customer installed equipment at one of the remote customer premises may include a plurality of modems which are connected to the four-wire lines by means of a distribution bridge and collection bridge pair, also known as a split data bridge, which serves to branch the four-wire line into a plurality of channels connected to the modems. Each channel can be provided with a tone activated detection circuit which may be separately addressed by a multi-frequency tone generator at the first customer premise. This tone activated detection circuit controls switching circuits to provide loop-back related tests such as conventional four-wire loop-back, data-streaming dropout or quiet termination, and a milliwatt test signal source in a predetermined sequence on command. Thus, each channel can be individually addressed, tested and dropped or returned to service as appropriate, all on command from the first location.

column12: Two way pressure relief valve with a primary valve and at least one vacuum valve.
column13: A pressure relief valve adapted to be mounted over an aperture in a container including a housing (3), a valve seat, and a valve assembly (8) which includes a primary valve (17) and at least one vacuum valve (35). The primary valve (17) includes a primary valve piston which is mounted for reciprocation within the housing (3) upon a ram shaft (9) which carries a ram piston (42). The said ram piston (42) is reciprocally mounted within a chamber (50) which can be pressurised. The primary valve piston is dimensioned and arranged such that said primary valve (17) is closed only when the primary valve piston contacts the valve seat. The primary valve piston is arranged to close when the air pressure in the pressurised chamber (50) exceeds a first predetermined value and to open when the pressure in the container exceeds a second predetermined value and the or each vacuum valve (35) is arranged to open when the pressure in the container is less than a third predetermined value.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR DATA STORAGE AND RETRIEVAL
column13: In a computer having one or more secondary storage devices attached thereto, a Finite Data Environment Processor (FDEP) manages Data Sets residing on the secondary storage devices and in memory using Set Lists (SLs) and General Record Pointers (GRPs). The Data Sets contain either data or logical organizational information. The Set Lists comprise Data Sets organized into a hierarchy. The General Record Pointers identify information in terms of Data Sets and records within them. Using the principal idea that a Data Set is uniquely identifiable, the present invention eliminates problems normally associated with referencing the location of data after the data has been moved.

Valves closing after predetermined flow.- A seat-action water-closet flushing-valve for use on board ship, railway trains, stations, &c., comprises a double-sided valve A operating between oppositely-disposed seatings 8, 9 on the inlet pipe 1 and the discharge pipe 2, respectively. The valve is operated from the closet seat 14 through a lever 19, rotary way-shaft 13, external link and arm 21, 22 and internal arm 12. column12: Method and system for terminating unnecessary processing of a conditional instruction in a processor
column13: A method and system for terminating unnecessary processing of at least one multi-clock conditional instruction in a processor. The conditional instruction is processed through a processing pipeline including at least a decode stage, an execute stage, and one or more intermediate processing stages therebetween. It is determined whether the conditional instruction is executable in the execute stage based on whether one or more conditions are fulfilled. If the conditional instruction is being processed in both the decode and execute stages, the conditional instruction is terminated in the decode stage if the conditional instruction is not to be executed in the execute stage. The conditional instruction may also be terminated in the intermediate processing stages. Early termination of such a conditional instruction saves processing resources and reduces power consumption of the processor.

column12: Method and system for predicting the execution of conditional instructions in a processor
column13: A method and system is disclosed for predicting whether a conditional instruction is to be executed in a processor. The processor processes instructions through processing stages including at least a decode stage, an execute stage, and one or more intermediate processing stages therebetween. First, a current condition status of the processor is detected, wherein the condition status shows whether one or more conditions for executing the conditional instruction have been satisfied. After detecting whether one or more associated instructions as being processed during the intermediate processing stages have impacted or will impact the conditions to be satisfied, it is determined whether the conditional instruction should be terminated at the decode stage based on the detected current condition status and the detected impact on the conditions due to the processing of the associated instructions. If it is predicted that there are unsatisfied conditions for executing the conditional instruction in the execute stage, the conditional instruction is terminated in the decode stage so as to avoid utilizing additional processor resources.

column12: Manufacture of carbonaceous moulding compositions suitable for extrusion and of moulded carbon products therefrom
column13: In the manufacture from coal of a carbonaceous moulding-composition particularly for extrusion, the finely-divided coal is mixed at an elevated temperature with a softening-agent which exercises a solvent action on the coal. The softening agent, which may form 10-35 per cent of the mixture, comprises at least one of the following: coal tar middle oil, heavy oil, anthracene oil, or pitch, benzene, naphthalene, anthracene, phenanthrene, or their derivatives (including phthalic acid esters and aryl esters of phosphoric acid), naphthenic and heterocyclic compounds, petroleum residues, soft bitumen, or chlorinated paraffin waxes. The coal is one containing up to 25 per cent, preferably 6-20 per cent of volatile matter and is ground to 80-150 mesh. Mixing is effected at 60-180 DEG C. for 4-8 hours. After coding a light oil such as naphtha and a dehydrogenating agent such as sulphur, selenium, or nitrobenzene may be added; in addition, to reduce swelling and to facilitate flow during moulding, a finely-divided carbonaceous substance such as carbon black or graphite may be included. After cooling to a solid billet, the mass can be extruded to the desired shape, preferably at room temperature. The article can then be dried by maintaining at a temperature of 100 DEG C. for 24 hours and is then fired under non-oxidizing conditions to a temperature of at least 550 DEG C. and preferably above 700 DEG C. Specifications 353,493, [Group XXXVII], 561,546, 595,759, 595,761, and 597,932 are referred to.

column12: Alarm assembly for product level gauge
column13: A gauge assembly for measuring the level of a liquid product in a storage tank includes a float member that is constructed and arranged to float on the liquid product in the storage tank, a housing that is constructed and arranged to be mounted on an exterior of the storage tank and a drum that is mounted inside the housing for rotation about an axis. A filament is wound about the drum, and extends through an opening defined in the housing to an attachment with a float member. A spring is provided for biasing the drum in a first rotary direction that will wind the filament onto the drum, whereby the drum will tend to pull the float member toward the housing, keeping the filament taut. A clock-type face is mounted on the housing, and has distance indicia marked there around that is in a base-twelve numbering system to represent feet and inches, rather than hours and minutes. A small hand is mounted to traverse the clock face to represent feet, and is connected to the drum via a gear train. A large hand is mounted to traverse the clock face to represent inches, and is also connected to the gear train. A novel alarm system for indicating when the storage tank is filled to a predetermined maximum level includes an alarm indicator mounted on the clock face to indicate a level of the float member at which the alarm will sound. The alarm indicator is ordinarily connected to the gear train, but may be adjusted with respect to the gear train, whereby a user will be able to manually adjust the level at which the alarm system will be actuated to correspond to a selected level in the storage tank.

column12: Radiotherapeutic apparatus with MRI and slip rings
column13: Radiotherapeutic apparatus (see figure 1) comprising: a patient support 10; magnetic coils 16 disposed around the patient support for creating a magnetic field; a radiation source 30 producing a beam of radiation directed toward the patient support and mounted on a gantry 28 rotatable around the patient support; and a plurality of slip rings 40, 42, 44 for conveying electrical power to the radiation source; a plurality of contacts 50, 52, 54 for electrically coupling the slip rings to the radiation source, and one or more non-conducting barriers 70, 72 between adjacent contacts for preventing formation of arcs between the contacts. The insulating barriers allow power to be delivered to the radiation source at an elevated voltage e.g. 10kV or higher, reducing the current in the slip rings and minimizing interference on the magnetic fields associated with the coils. A step-down transformer between the slip rings and the radiation source and/or a step-up transformer before the slip rings can be provided to "correct" the voltages. An insulating barrier 60, 62 may also be between the slip rings. The magnetic coils allow patient location monitoring using MRI.

The radiation source may be a linear accelerator. Preferably the electrical power provided to the radiation source 30 via the slip ring 40,42,44 is at a voltage of at least 10kv. In description, magnetic coils 16,18,20 are part of a MRI apparatus and the current required by the radiation source at standard supply voltages is high enough for slip ring generation of stray magnetic fields that interfere with those of magnetic coils 16,18,20; the advantage of the slip ring and transformer arrangement is that the step up transformer, by increasing the voltage supplied to the slip ring, also causes a reduction of the slip ring current, thereby reducing the stray interfering magnetic field level and improving image quality.

column12: RETRACTABLE LIFELINE SAFETY DEVICE
column13: A retractable lifeline safety device usable by workers performing tasks at great heights above the ground. The mechanical components of the safety device are contained within a sealed housing that is filled with a viscous fluid. The sealed housing prevents the introduction of dirt, moisture and other foreign matter into the mechanical mechanism of the safety device, reducing the likelihood that those components may be fouled by dirt and corrosion, which in turn could greatly reduce the effectiveness of the safety device. The safety device is attached to the structure on which the worker is performing the task, and a lifeline such as a cable is withdrawn from the housing thereof, the end of which is attached to a belt or harness worn by the worker. The cable may be easily drawn out of the housing in response to the worker moving about normally in the appropriate work space, and the cable is automatically drawn back into the housing of the safety device as the worker draws closer thereto. However, should the worker fall, a brake within the safety device is automatically engaged by a centrifugal clutch, stopping the worker's descent.

column12: Method and system for terminating unnecessary processing of a conditional instruction in a processor
column13: A method and system is for terminating unnecessary processing of at least one multi-clock conditional instruction in a processor. The conditional instruction is processed through a processing pipeline including at least a decode stage, an execute stage, and one or more intermediate processing stages therebetween. It is determined whether conditional instruction is executable in the execute stage based on whether one or more conditions are fulfilled. If the conditional instruction is being processed in both decode and execute stages, the conditional instruction is terminated in the decode stage if the conditional instruction is not to be executed in the execute stage. The conditional instruction may also be terminated in the intermediate processing stages. Early termination of such a conditional instruction saves processing resources and reduces power consumption of the processor.

column12: Method and system for predicting the execution of conditional instructions in a processor
column13: A method and system is disclosed for predicting whether a conditional instruction is to be executed in a processor. The processor processes instructions through processing stages including at least a decode stage, an execute stage, and one or more intermediate processing stages therebetween. First, a current condition status of the processor is detected, wherein the condition status shows whether one or more conditions for executing the conditional instruction have been satisfied. After detecting whether one or more associated instructions as being processed during the intermediate processing stages have impacted or will impact the conditions to be satisfied, it is determined whether the conditional instruction should be terminated at the decode stage based on the detected current condition status and the detected impact on the conditions due to the processing of the associated instructions. If it is predicted that there are unsatisfied conditions for executing the conditional instruction in the execute stage, the conditional instruction is terminated in the decode stage so as to avoid utilizing additional processor resources.

column12: STORAGE TANK FOR CRYOGENIC LIQUIDS
column13: The storage tank for cryogenic liquids incorporates an ullage vessel that provides for an ullage space. The ullage vessel is in communication through an ullage line to a fill line that provides cryogen to a cryogen space. The junction where the ullage line and fill line meet is of a certain cross-sectional area. Downstream of the junction within the fill line, measured in reference to the direction of cryogen flow during a course of filling the cryogen space, is of a greater cross-sectional area than is the case at the junction. This creates a pressure reduction at the junction during a course of filling that causes a net flow of material from the ullage space over the course of filling. Once the cryogen tank is liquid full causing cryogen to be redirected down the ullage line, the smaller cross-sectional area of the ullage line compared to the fill line causes a reduction in flow of cryogen which is detected by the fill pump causing filling to stop providing the ullage space. A means of draining the ullage vessel prior to and during filling of the storage tank is provided.

column12: DIGITAL VIDEO RECORDING
column13: Apparatus for storing a video signal includes means for repeatedly determining a portion of the picture area which contains moving information. Only the portion of the video signal which corresponds to this area containing moving information is then stored. The video signal comprises luminance and chrominance components and may have an associated matte signal. The apparatus includes means for recording the luminance and chrominance components and the matte in synchronism on a common record medium. A camera produces a video signal at an output and means for recording this signal is also provided. The camera also includes means for detecting the location and/or orientation of the camera and generating signals dependent thereon. These signals are recorded in synchronism with the video signal. Apparatus for generating a video signal is used to provide a composite picture in combination with a video signal which has camera location and/or orientation data associated with it. The system may include means for computing objects to be included in the video signal and will also include means for producing a matte associated with that computed object for each pixel which that object intersects.

column12: APPAREIL POUR LA FABRICATION D'UNE BANDE DE SILICIUM
column13: Cet appareil permet d'améliorer le développement d'une bande réalisable en modifiant les ouvertures 15, 16 et 29 du couvercle afin de maîtriser les pertes de chaleur à l'interface de tirage pour réaliser une épaisseur uniforme de toute la bande tirée à travers la fente 14, en particulier dans les régions de la bande contigus aux dendrites. Dans les configurations non modifiées des ouvertures du couvercle, on constate que les régions amincies de la bande contigus aux dendrites sont à l'origine d'une dégradation du cristal aboutissant en fin de compte à l'interruption du tirage de la bande. Ainsi, l'amincissement contigu aux dendrites est réduit et les cas de dégradation de cristal sont réduits de la même manière.

column12: Device for protecting a differential pressure sensor
column13: A device (4) is provided for protecting a differential pressure sensing apparatus (1). The device has first and second supply ports (6,8) for connection to pressure sources and first and second sensor ports (18,20) for connection to a differential pressure sensing apparatus (1). A first conduit (22) fluidly connects the first supply port (6) and the first sensor port (18) and a second conduit (24) fluidly connects the second supply port (8) and the second sensor port (20). A first relief conduit (32) and second relief conduit (34) fluidly connect the first conduit (22) and the second conduit (24). A first elastomeric one-way pressure relief valve (36) is arranged to block the first relief conduit (22) unless the pressure in the first conduit (22) exceeds the pressure in the second conduit (24) by a first predetermined amount. A second elastomeric one-way pressure relief valve (38) is arranged to block the second relief conduit (28) unless the pressure in the second conduit (24) exceeds the pressure in the first conduit (22) by a second predetermined amount. An elastomeric one-way pressure relief valve (36) is also provided. A further invention relates to a specific elastomeric valve construction in which an elastomeric sleeve or sheath is placed over the valve body, covering the exit port of the valve body. Excess pressure caused the sheath to deform outwardly allowing fluid flow. The sleeve contains at least one gap and may be formed by several O-rings.

column12: Method and system for predicting the execution of conditional instructions in a processor
column13: A method and system is disclosed for predicting whether a conditional instruction is to be executed in a processor. The processor processes instructions through processing stages including at least a decode stage, an execute stage, and one or more intermediate processing stages therebetween. First, a current condition status of the processor is detected, wherein the condition status shows whether one or more conditions for executing the conditional instruction have been satisfied. After detecting whether one or more associated instructions as being processed during the intermediate processing stages have impacted or will impact the conditions to be satisfied, it is determined whether the conditional instruction should be terminated at the decode stage based on the detected current condition status and the detected impact on the conditions due to the processing of the associated instructions. If it is predicted that there are unsatisfied conditions for executing the conditional instruction in the execute stage, the conditional instruction is terminated in the decode stage so as to avoid utilizing additional processor resources.

column13: 26,887. Duncan, H. M., and Macauley, C. R. Dec. 5. Type; monotype machines.-Relates to typecasting machines, particularly to "monotype" type casting and composing machines such as are described in Specification No. 13,267, A.D. 1897, and consists of pneumatically-controlled means for casting quads and spaces having bodies shorter than those of the character types. Fig. 1 shows a section through the mould of a monotype machine, the movable mould blade B having a sliding part B' with a nose B<2> for closing the top of the mould cavity A<3>, as described in Specification No. 18,848, A.D. 1902. The blade B is operated in the usual manner. The part B' has a notch B<4> engaged by one end of a horizontal lever B<5>, Fig. 3, the other end of which is engaged by a pin on a rod C<2> having a piston C' fitting an air cylinder C. The rod C<2> is normally pulled by a spring C<15> to hold the part B' retracted while the mould blade B operates in the usual manner to cast character types. The cylinder C has an air-inlet opening C<6> and an exhaust outlet C<7>. The outlet C<7> is provided with a valve on the lower end of a rod C<9> raised by a spring C<12>. Engaging the upper end of rod C<9> is a sleeve C<13> on a projection from the arm which is depressed to operate the centering pin by which the positioned matrix is finally centered and held tightly on to the mould during each cast. The depression of the sleeve C<13> also closes the valve, and if compressed air be at the same time admitted through the opening C<6>, the piston is operated to project the nose B<2> into the mould cavity. The admission of compressed air to the cylinder C is controlled by a valve actuated by compressed air when certain pairs of perforations in the record strip come into action. Fig. 11 shows a section of a record strip with four pairs of perforations for actuating the valve, a pair a, b for unjustified spaces, a pair a, c for spaces affected by the justifying-mechanism, a pair a, d for en quads, and a pair a, e for em quads. Any of these perforations singly may be used in the combinations for casting character types Fig. 5 shows the valve; which has an air inlet D<1>, and an outlet D<2> connected with the inlet C<6>. A valve D<4> on a rod D<6> pressed by a spring D<5> normally closes communication between the inlet and outlet D', D<2>. On the rod D<6> are two pistons D<9>, D<10> moving in cylinders each having an inlet D<11> and outlets D<12>, D<13> The spring D<5> is of such strength that it prevents the movement of the valverod except when compressed air is admitted simultaneously through both of the openings D<11>. One of the openings D<11> is controlled by the perforations a, and the other by all of the perforations b, c, d, e, so that the valve D' is opened when any pair of perforations shown in Fig. 11 comes into action.

column12: Method and system for terminating unnecessary processing of a conditional instruction in a processor
column13: A method and system is for terminating unnecessary processing of at least one multi-clock conditional instruction in a processor. The conditional instruction is processed through a processing pipeline including at least a decode stage, an execute stage, and one or more intermediate processing stages therebetween. It is determined whether conditional instruction is executable in the execute stage based on whether one or more conditions are fulfilled. If the conditional instruction is being processed in both decode and execute stages, the conditional instruction is terminated in the decode stage if the conditional instruction is not to be executed in the execute stage. The conditional instruction may also be terminated in the intermediate processing stages. Early termination of such a conditional instruction saves processing resources and reduces power consumption of the processor.

column13: "UNIDADE DE TANQUE CRIOGêNICO PARA RETER UM FLUIDO CRIOGêNICO, E, MéTODO PARA CARREGAR UM ESPAçO DE ARMAZENAMENTO CRIOGêNICO COM UM FLUIDO CRIOGêNICO". O tanque de armazenamento para líquido criogênico incorpora um vaso com espaço morto que provê um espaço morto. O vaso com espaço morto fica em comunicação através de uma linha com espaço morto com uma linha de carregamento que provê criogênio para um espaço criogênico. A junção na qual a linha com espaço morto e a linha de carregamento se encontram tem uma certa área de seção transversal. A jusante da junção, dentro da linha de carregamento, medida com referência à direção do fluxo criogênico durante um curso de carregamento do espaço criogênico, a área da seção transversal é maior do que a da junção. Isto cria uma redução de pressão na junção durante um curso de carregamento que causa um fluxo líquido de material do espaço morto durante o curso de carregamento. Uma vez que o tanque criogênico esteja cheio de lìquido, fazendo com que o criogênio seja redirecionado pela linha com espaço morto, a área de seção transversal menor da linha com espaço morto, em comparação com a linha de carregamento, causa uma redução no fluxo de criogênio, que é detectada pela bomba de carregamento, fazendo com que o carregamento para o espaço morto seja interrompido. Um meio de drenar o vaso com espaço morto, antes e durante carregamento do tanque de armazenamento, é provido.

column12: Craniosacral Therapeutic Apparatus
column13: An apparatus ( 10 ) for a craniosacral therapy technique is provided. The apparatus ( 10 ) is configured as a headrest for a human being to rest their head on. The apparatus ( 10 ) is comprised of a resilient monocoque structure having a sidewall made from a thermo-plastic elastomer. The apparatus ( 10 ) is comprised of a base portion ( 105 ), two semi-spherical shaped protuberances ( 120, 130 ) extending upward from the base portion ( 105 ), and a channel ( 125 ) formed between the two protuberances ( 120, 130 ). The adjacent protuberances ( 120, 130 ) put stabilizing bi-lateral pressure on the occipital region of the head to induce what is known as a “still point”. After a rest period of up to twenty minutes, the pressure on the occipital region is removed. The release of the apparatus ( 10 ) allows production of cerebrospinal fluids which then gently flushes these areas of tissue restrictions or adhesions thereby improving circulation and facilitating greater balance and function of the central nervous system.

column12: STORAGE TANK FOR CRYOGENIC LIQUIDS
column13: The storage tank for cryogenic liquids incorporates an ullage vessel that provides for an ullage space. The ullage vessel is in communication through an ullage line t:o a fill line that provides cryogen to a cryogen space. The junction where the ullage line and fill line meet is of a certain cross-sectional area. Downstream of the junction within the fill line, measured in reference to the direction of cryogen flow during a course of filling the cryogen space, is of a greater cross-sectional area than is the case at the junction. This creates a pressure reduction at the junction during a course of filling that causes a net flow of material from the ullage space over the course of filling. Once the cryogen tank is liquid full causing cryogen to be redirected down the ullage line, the smaller cross-sectional area of the ullage line compared to the fill line causes a reduction in flow of cryogen which is detected by the fill pump causing filling to stop providing the ullage space. A means of draining the ullage vessel prior to and during filling of the storage tank is provided.

column12: Clutch control system
column13: A clutch control system for the automatic control of a motor vehicle clutch which connects an engine with a gearbox under the control of a driver operated gear ratio selector lever. The control system controls both initial clutch take-up on starting of the vehicle, clutch re-engagement following each ratio change, clutch disengagement on movement of the gear selector lever to change the operative ratio of the gearbox, and clutch disengagement on the coming to rest of the vehicle. The clutch control system also warms (50, c) the operator if he attempts to drive away in a designated non take-up gear or in any gear in a predetermined abusive manner and may be arranged to promote rapid engagement or disengagement of the clutch in certain abusive conditions to reduce energy generation in the clutch. <IMAGE>

column12: Manufacture of carbon moulded bodies
column13: Carbon moulded bodies are produced by mixing powdered coal at an elevated temperature with one or more plasticizing agents consisting substantially of hydrocarbons, moulding at an elevated temperature at which the mixture is plastic and then firing under nonoxidizing conditions at a controlled rate of temperature rise. Plasticizers specified are pitches, tars, coal tar distillates such as naphtha, benzene and anthracene oil, and volatile solvents. Swell inhibitors as disclosed in Specifications 595,759 and 595,760 may be included. Solid plasticizers are ground to pass 1/8 -inch B.S.S. screen, and the coal should all pass 100 B.S.S. screen. Mixing temperature is 100-150 DEG C., but the plasticizer must be soft. Prior to firing the shape is dried at 60-100 DEG C, and the rate of firing is 1/2 DEG C. per minute to 600 DEG C., and 2 DEG C. per minute to 1200 DEG C., the latter temperature being maintained for 30 minutes. Specification 595,761 is referred to. Reference has been directed by the Comptroller to Specification 648,539.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the preparation of carbon monofluoride
column13: Small amounts of fluoro- and fluoro-chlorocarbons and carbon monofluoride are prepared by submitting carbon to the joint action of fluorine and chlorine, the molar ratio of fluorine to chlorine being in the range 0.2-2 1/2 mols. of fluorine per mol. of chlorine, at a temperature of at least 400 DEG C. but less than 500 DEG C. The molar ratio F:Cl may be 0.75:1 to 1.25:1, but preferably an equimolar ratio is employed, and the fluorine and chlorine may be a mixture, an interhalogen compound, e.g. chlorine monofluoride, or a mixture of the latter with one of the elements. The halogens may be preheated to 400-500 DEG C. in a nickel preheater and are contacted with graphite in a shallow nickel boat in a nickel reactor at 425-475 DEG C. The effluent gases may be passed through traps held at different temperatures to recover chlorine, which is recycled, and the small amounts of fluoro- and fluoro-chlorocarbons. Solid products having formul CF0,92 and CF1,03 are referred to. Alternatively, the halogens may be passed through a bed of graphite which may be fluidized. The solid carbon monofluoride may be decomposed by heating at low pressure, e.g. 500-600 DEG C. at 0.5 cm. Hg, yields a mixture of fluorocarbons of average molecular composition C2,5 F6,8 (CF4, C2F4, C2F6, C3F8, C4F10, C5F12, C6F14, C5F10, and C6F12) and a mixture of fluoroaromatic compounds having condensed nuclei. Heating in nitrogen at 500-600 DEG C. yields a mixture of fluorocarbons of average molecular composition C2,5F7,9, the above mixture of fluoro-aromatic compounds having condensed nuclei, and a fluoro-carbon oil believed to be a mixture of fluoroaromatic compounds having condensed nuclei with aliphatic side chains. Heating at 400-600 DEG C. in chlorine yields fully halogenated fluoro-, or fluorochloro-derivatives of methane, ethane, propane, butane, pentane, and hexane, containing not more than 2 chlorine atoms per molecule, a compound of empirical formula C17,8F18Cl, and the mixture of fluoroaromatic compounds having condensed nuclei.ALSO:Carbon monofluoride is prepared by submitting carbon to the joint action of fluorine and chlorine, the molar ratio of fluorine to chlorine being in the range 0.2-2 1/2 moles of fluorine per mole of chlorine, at a temperature of at least 400 DEG C. but less than 500 DEG C. The halogens may be preheated to 400 DEG -500 DEG C. in a nickel preheater, and are contacted with graphite in a shallow nickel boat in a nickel reactor at 425 DEG -475 DEG C. Heating in nitrogen at 500 DEG -600 DEG C. yields a mixture of fluorocarbons of average molecular composition C2.5F7.9, the above mixture of fluoroaromatic compounds having condensed nuclei, and a fluorocarbon oil believed to be a mixture of fluoroaromatic compounds having condensed nuclei with aliphatic side chains. column12: Apparatus for silicon web growth of higher output and improved growth stability
column13: This disclosure describes an apparatus to improve the web growth attainable from prior web growth configurations. This apparatus modifies the heat loss at the growth interface in a manner that minimizes thickness variations across the web, especially regions of the web adjacent to the two bounding dendrites. In the unmodified configuration, thinned regions of web, adjacent to the dendrites, were found to be the origin of crystal degradation which ultimately led to termination of the web growth. According to the present invention, thinning adjacent to the dendrites is reduced and the incidence of crystal degradation is similarly reduced.

column12: STORAGE TANK FOR CRYOGENIC LIQUIDS
column13: The storage tank for cryogenic liquids incorporates an ullage vessel that provides for an ullage space. The ullage vessel is in communication through an ullage line to a fill line that provides cryogen to a cryogen space. The junction where the ullage line and fill line meet is of a certain cross-sectional area. Downstream of the junction within the fill line, measured in reference to the direction of cryogen flow during a coruse of filling the cryogen space, is of a greater cross-sectional area than is the case at the junction. This creates a pressure reduction at the junction during a course of filling that causes a net flow of material from the ullage space over the course of filling. Once the cryogen tank is liquid full causing cryogen to be redirected down the ullage line, the smaller cross-sectional area of the ullage line compared to the fill line causes a reduction in flow of cryogen which is detected by the fill pump causing filling to stop providing the ullage space. A means of draining the ullage vessel prior to and during filling of the storage tank is provided.

The clutch control system also warns (50.c) the operator if he attempts to drive away in a designated non take-up gear or in any gear in a predetermined abusive manner and may be arranged to promote rapid engagement or disengagement of the clutch in certain abusive conditions to reduce energy generation in the clutch.

column13: 18,848. Duncan, H. M., Prichard, C. H., and Macauley, C. R. Aug. 27. Type; monotype and like machines.-Relates to typecasting moulds, especially such as are employed in monotype machines (Specification No. 8633, A.D. 1899), and consists of an arrangement by which quads are cast shorter in length than the type bodies. Fig. 1 shows part of a monotype machine in which B is the mould and C the actuating- lever for the matrix-centering pin. The lever C is pivoted at A', and is actuated by a lever C' &c. The mould B, Fig. 3, has a mould cavity B<1>, one wall of which is formed by the end of the mould blade or plunger E, E', Fig. 4. The two parts E, E<1> of the plunger are mounted to slide one on the other, and when a quad is about to be cast, the part E<1> is moved forwards on the part E so that its end E<11> forms a cover to and shortens the mould cavity B<1>. The parts E, E' are formed with slots E<2> in which engages the cross-pin G, Figs. 5 and 6, by which the plunger is connected with its operating- slide. The cross-pin G has two lateral enlargements or cams G', G', and, when the pin is moved longitudinally in the slot E<2>, these cams move the part E<1> to one of its two positions on the part E. The pin G is fixed on the end of a pin G<3>, into the other end of which is screwed a pin G', on which slides a box or cylinder G<5> pressed towards the pin G<3> by a spring G<6>. The pin is moved longitudinally by a lever G<9> engaging the lugs G<7> and operated by a lever G<11> rod G<13>, lever G", and cam H. The movement of the pin G is normally prevented, so that the box G<5> only is moved against the pressure of the spring G<6> by the cam H &c. This is effected by a spring arm K engaging a groove in the pin G<3>. When the die case D moves into position for casting a quad, a pin D<2> projecting from it engages a rod N, pivoted on a lever M, and moves its upper end N<2> into engagement with the lever C. When the lever C descends, it depresses the rod N and operates the lever M, and this operates a lever L, the end L<2> of which engages and depresses the spring arm K from engagement with the pin G<3>. The pin G', G is then moved by the cam H &c. until its cam G' moves forwards the part E<1> of the mould plunger.

column12: CONTROL FOR COMMUNICATION SYSTEMS TRANSMITTING AND RECEIVING SIGNALS WITH SUBSTANTIALLY NO SIDEBANDS
column13: Modulation of signals includes substantially no side bands in a frequency domain. Circuitry in a communication system of same includes a control signal derived from a carrier, or vice versa, to modulate an input signal. A preferred carrier embodies a sine wave while the preferred control signal is a square wave. A frequency of the control signal includes once or twice multiple integers of the frequency of the sine wave, particularly when impressing data on the carrier per every full or half wave cycle of the sine wave, respectively. An input signal adjusted in frequency to match the carrier frequency is used as an input to a gain adjustable module to adjust gain thereof. The carrier is another input to the module and the output of the module is the signal having substantially no sidebands. Transmitters, receivers, systems and communication medium are also disclosed.

column12: Processing wellbore data to determine subterranean characteristics
column13: A computer system and method for determining subterranean rock composition is described in which user input data is received having a plurality of parameters defining a desired subterranean rock composition from a wellbore. Data associated with at least one geologic environment is received, which data contains data acquired from at least one wellbore. An analytical analysis is then conducted by a computer processor utilizing the user input data and the received geologic environment data to determine a match between the user desired subterranean rock composition and the received geologic environment data. Output graphic data is then determined and generated, based at least in part on the analytical analysis, on a computer graphical display consisting of a two-dimensional (2D) graphical representation indicating a region of the geologic environment having a match between the user desired subterranean rock composition and the received geologic environment data.

column12: GENERATING HYDROCARBON CHANCE MAPPING
column13: This disclosure presents methods and systems to perform fairway analysis on a computing system to automate tasks. The automation of the fairway analysis can reduce bias and uncertainty introduced by a user using their own set of assumptions, estimations, and preferred sequencing of rules and algorithms. The described processes can receive initial input parameters describing the area of interest (A0I) and a geological age range. The processes can retrieve appropriate geological and stratigraphic parameters using the initial input parameters. The combined input parameters can then be geoprocessed using age-aware rules and a determined sequence of algorithms and rules to generate synthesized geological data that can be upscaled and transformed into one or more chance maps indicating the presence and effectiveness of various hydrocarbon elements. The chance maps can be amalgamated and processed to produce a prospective map indicating the likelihood of success of further exploration of the specified AOI.

column12: GENERATING HYDROCARBON CHANCE MAPPING
column13: This disclosure presents methods and systems to perform fairway analysis on a computing system to automate tasks. The automation of the fairway analysis can reduce bias and uncertainty introduced by a user using their own set of assumptions, estimations, and preferred sequencing of rules and algorithms. The described processes can receive initial input parameters describing the area of interest (AOI) and a geological age range. The processes can retrieve appropriate geological and stratigraphic parameters using the initial input parameters. The combined input parameters can then be geoprocessed using age-aware rules and a determined sequence of algorithms and rules to generate synthesized geological data that can be upscaled and transformed into one or more chance maps indicating the presence and effectiveness of various hydrocarbon elements. The chance maps can be amalgamated and processed to produce a prospective map indicating the likelihood of success of further exploration of the specified AOI.

column12: CONTROL FOR COMMUNICATION SYSTEMS TRANSMITTING AND RECEIVING SIGNALS WITH SUBSTANTIALLY NO SIDEBANDS
column13: Modulation of signals includes substantially no side bands in a frequency domain. Circuitry in a communication system of same includes a control signal derived from a carrier, or vice versa, to modulate an input signal. A preferred carrier embodies a sine wave while the preferred control signal is a square wave. A frequency of the control signal includes once or twice multiple integers of the frequency of the sine wave, particularly when impressing data on the carrier per every full or half wave cycle of the sine wave, respectively. An input signal adjusted in frequency to match the carrier frequency is used as an input to a gain adjustable module to adjust gain thereof. The carrier is another input to the module and the output of the module is the signal having substantially no sidebands. Transmitters, receivers, systems and communication medium are also disclosed.

column12: Generating hydrocarbon chance mapping
column13: A method of fairway analysis comprises receiving 320 initial input parameters describing the area of interest (AOI) and a geological age range. The processes can retrieve appropriate geological and stratigraphic parameters using the initial input parameters. The combined input parameters can then be geoprocessed 330 using age-aware rules and a determined sequence of algorithms and rules to generate synthesized geological data that can be upscaled 350 and transformed into one or more chance maps indicating the presence and effectiveness of various hydrocarbon elements. The algorithms use a stratigraphic framework e.g. sequence stratigraphic, chronostratigraphic or lithostatigraphic framework. The chance maps can be amalgamated and processed to produce a prospective map 360 indicating the likelihood of success of further exploration of the specified AOI. The chance maps may be stacked GDE, element presence, thermal maturity, kitchen, charge or reservoir effectiveness.

column12: Valve actuating means
column13: 786,511. Valve-actuating mechanism. AUDLEY ENGINEERING CO., Ltd. Jan. 17, 1956 [Jan. 27, 1955], No. 2454/55. Class 135. Valve-actuating mechanism comprises a pair of relatively slidable and angularly movable lever parts a, b which can be locked together to form a simple lever or can be unlocked so that one of the lever parts co-operates with a notched member to give a compound lever action. In Fig. 1, the lever part a is secured to the spindle c of the valve closure member and has a slot d to accommodate a pivot pin e which interconnects the two lever parts and is secured to the lever part b which is actuated by hand. The part b has two holes for engagement by a locking pin f. As shown, the two lever parts a, bare interlocked for, operation as a simple lever. If the pin f is withdrawn from the hole g, and a pin i secured to the inner end of the part b is moved into engagement with one of the notches j on a segmental or circular plate k secured to the valve casing a compound lever action may be obtained. If the pin f is then inserted in the hole h the valve closure member is locked against movement. In a modification, the slot d is formed in a bracket fixed to the valve casing and the lever part a is formed as a notched circular or segmental plate with a series of holes for selective engagement by a locking pin which also engages a hole in the lever part b.

column12: PROCESSING WELLBORE DATA TO DETERMINE SUBTERRANEAN CHARACTERISTICS
column13: A computer system and method for determining subterranean rock composition is described in which user input data is received having a plurality of parameters defining a desired subterranean rock composition from a wellbore. Data associated with at least one geologic environment is received, which data contains data acquired from at least one wellbore. An analytical analysis is then conducted by a computer processor utilizing the user input data and the received geologic environment data to determine a match between the user desired subterranean rock composition and the received geologic environment data. Output graphic data is then determined and generated, based at least in part on the analytical analysis, on a computer graphical display consisting of a two-dimensional (2D) graphical representation indicating a region of the geologic environment having a match between the user desired subterranean rock composition and the received geologic environment data.

column13: Some aspects of the present invention are directed to unique products and methods for treating fistulae and other passageways and openings in the body. In some preferred forms, an inventive construct will include an elongate graft body that incorporates a plurality of sheet or sheet-like segments. The plurality of sheet or sheet-like segments, in some arrangements, will be stacked in a generally longitudinal direction along the length of the plug body, and optionally, the segments will be received over one or more elongate elements. column12: Casting of polymeric materials
column13: Shaped articles are made from diisocyanate-modified polyesters by transferring a diisocyanate-modified polyester while in a fluid state into a closed mould in the presence of an oxidizing agent and curing the polyester by heat to an extent sufficient to permit the removal of the article from the mould. After the article has been removed from the mould it may be further cured by heating in air. The oxidizing agent may be applied to the surface of the mould prior to the introduction of the modified polyester, or the oxidizing agent may be mixed with the polyester before it is transferred to the mould, e.g. mixed with the modified polyester at the same time as the addition of the ethylene or butylene glycol cross-linking agent. Oxidizing agents mentioned are lead oxide, ferric oxide, barium peroxide, potassium nitrate, potassium chlorate, benzoyl peroxide, cumene hydroperoxide, tert.-butyl perbenzoate, cyclohexanone peroxide, cobalt naphthenate, and lead tetraacetate. In addition to the ethylene or butylene glycol mentioned above, other curing agents, such as formaldehyde, paraformaldehyde, quinone oximes, dinitrobenzene and trinitrobenzene may be present. The diisocyanate-modified polyester is preferably made by melting a polyester of acid value of 2 or less and hydroxyl value of about 40, e.g. a condensation polymer of adipic acid and ethylene glycol, adding to the ester naphthalene 1,5-diisocyanate in the presence of an organic acid, e.g. adipic acid, as a reaction retardant, and finally mixing the reaction product with dry ethylene or butylene glycol. The product may be porous.ALSO:Di-isocyanate - modified polyester is transferred in a fluid state into a closed mould in the presence of an oxidizing agent, and the polyester is cured by heat to an extent sufficient to permit the removal of the article from the mould. The oxidizing agent may be applied to the surface of the mould and the moulded product may be porous.
